Private Limited Company Registered—What Next? A 90-Day Compliance Guide for Founders

Receiving the Certificate of Incorporation is an important milestone. Your business now has a legal identity, a Corporate Identity Number and the ability to enter into contracts in its own name.

But incorporation is not the finishing line.

The first few weeks after registration establish the legal and financial foundation of your company. Several post-incorporation requirements must be completed within prescribed timelines, while others depend on your business activity, location, employee strength and turnover.

This founder-friendly guide explains what ordinarily needs to be completed during the first 90 days after registering a Private Limited Company in India.

Quick takeaway: Incorporation creates the company. Post-incorporation compliance makes it operational, organised and legally sustainable.

A Quick Post-Incorporation Timeline
Timeline	Important action
Immediately after incorporation	Organise incorporation documents and activate the company bank account
Within 30 days	Hold the first Board meeting
Within 30 days	Appoint the first statutory auditor
Within 30 days	Complete registered-office verification, where pending
Within two months	Issue share certificates to subscribers
Within 180 days	File the declaration for commencement of business in Form INC-20A, where applicable
As applicable	Obtain GST, Shops and Establishments, Professional Tax, IEC and sector-specific registrations
From Day 1	Maintain proper books, invoices, contracts and statutory records
1. Organise the Company’s Incorporation Records

Begin by creating a secure digital and physical incorporation folder.

It should ordinarily contain:

Certificate of Incorporation;
Memorandum of Association;
Articles of Association;
PAN and TAN documents;
Director Identification Number details;
Digital Signature Certificates;
registered-office documents;
subscriber and director identity documents;
incorporation forms and challans;
professional engagement records; and
copies of approvals received during incorporation.

These documents will repeatedly be required for banking, taxation, investment, vendor onboarding, payment-gateway activation, government registrations and future ROC filings.

Maintain one controlled master folder rather than allowing documents to remain scattered across email accounts and messaging applications.

2. Activate the Company Bank Account

A company is a separate legal entity. Its money should therefore remain separate from the personal funds of its directors and shareholders.

Complete the opening or activation of the company’s current account as early as possible. Banks commonly require the Certificate of Incorporation, PAN, constitutional documents, registered-office proof, Board authorisation and KYC documents of authorised signatories.

Once the account is active:

subscribers should transfer their agreed share-subscription money;
each payment should be traceable to the relevant subscriber;
bank statements and payment proofs should be preserved;
business receipts and expenditure should flow through the company account; and
personal and company expenditure should not be mixed.

Subscriber payment evidence is especially important for filing the declaration for commencement of business.

3. Confirm the Registered Office and Company Disclosures

A company must maintain a registered office capable of receiving official communications. Verification of the registered office is required within 30 days of incorporation.

The company’s name and registered-office address should also be displayed at its place of business. Its official letters, notices and publications should carry prescribed details such as the company name, registered-office address, Corporate Identity Number, contact information and website address, where applicable.

Check the following:

Is the company’s name displayed outside the registered office?
Can postal and regulatory communications be received there?
Is the address consistent across MCA, bank and tax records?
Do invoices and letterheads contain the correct legal name and CIN?
Is the official company email account functioning?
Has any change of address been properly documented and filed?

Small inconsistencies at this stage often become larger problems during bank verification, GST registration or regulatory inspection.

4. Hold the First Board Meeting

Every company is generally required to hold its first Board meeting within 30 days from incorporation. The Companies Act also prescribes continuing Board-meeting requirements, subject to relaxations available to certain classes such as One Person Companies, small companies and dormant companies.

The first Board meeting commonly deals with:

taking note of the Certificate of Incorporation;
taking note of the Memorandum and Articles;
confirming the registered office;
authorising operation of the bank account;
recording receipt of subscription money;
appointing the first statutory auditor;
taking directors’ disclosures on record;
approving issuance of share certificates;
authorising maintenance of statutory registers;
approving preliminary incorporation expenses;
appointing authorised signatories;
approving accounting and administrative arrangements; and
authorising the filing of INC-20A.

Proper notice, agenda papers, attendance records, resolutions and minutes should be maintained. A meeting should not exist merely on paper; its records should accurately reflect the decisions taken by the Board.

5. Appoint the First Statutory Auditor

For a company other than a government company, the Board of Directors is ordinarily required to appoint the first auditor within 30 days from registration.

If the Board fails to do so, the members must be informed and may appoint the auditor within the statutory period through an extraordinary general meeting. The first auditor ordinarily holds office until the conclusion of the first Annual General Meeting.

Founders sometimes assume that an auditor is required only after the company begins earning substantial revenue. That assumption is incorrect.

Even an early-stage or non-revenue company must maintain proper financial records and comply with the audit and annual-filing framework applicable to it.

The auditor’s written consent and eligibility confirmation should be obtained and preserved with the company’s records.

6. Issue Share Certificates to Subscribers

A Private Limited Company limited by shares must issue share certificates to the subscribers to its Memorandum within two months from incorporation.

Before issuing them, verify:

the subscriber’s correct legal name;
number and class of shares;
face value of each share;
certificate number;
distinctive numbers, where relevant;
amount paid;
date of issue;
Board authorisation;
authorised signatures; and
applicable stamp-duty requirements.

The register of members should correspond with the share certificates and the company’s constitutional documents.

A share certificate is not merely a decorative document. It is evidence of a member’s shareholding and should be prepared, authorised, stamped and preserved properly.

7. File INC-20A for Commencement of Business

A company having share capital and covered by Section 10A must file a declaration for commencement of business within 180 days from incorporation.

Before filing, every subscriber to the Memorandum should have paid the value of the shares agreed to be taken. The company should also have completed its registered-office verification.

Until the requirement is fulfilled, the company should not commence business or exercise borrowing powers. Failure can attract monetary penalties and may expose the company to strike-off action where the Registrar has reasonable cause to believe that it is not carrying on business or operations.

Form INC-20A generally requires:

the company’s CIN and registered-office particulars;
a Board authorisation;
subscriber payment evidence;
a director’s digital signature;
certification by the prescribed practising professional; and
regulatory approval details where the business is subject to a sectoral regulator.

The notified form specifically recognises subscriber proof of payment as a mandatory attachment.

Do not wait until the final week of the 180-day period. Bank activation, subscriber transfers, document collection and professional certification may take time.

8. Maintain Statutory Registers and Corporate Records

A company must maintain prescribed registers, including a register of members and, where relevant, registers relating to debenture holders and other security holders.

Depending on the company’s structure and activities, records may include:

register of members;
register of directors and key managerial personnel;
register of loans, guarantees and investments;
register of contracts and related-party arrangements;
register of charges;
attendance registers;
Board and general-meeting minutes;
share-certificate records;
disclosure forms; and
copies of statutory filings and acknowledgements.

These records should be updated when the relevant transaction or event occurs. Reconstructing them several years later is far more difficult and expensive than maintaining them correctly from the beginning.

9. Begin Proper Accounting From Day One

Books of account should not begin only when the company earns its first profit.

The Companies Act requires companies to maintain books and supporting records that explain their transactions and present a true and fair view of their affairs. The books are to be maintained on an accrual basis and according to the double-entry system of accounting.

From the first transaction, maintain:

sales invoices;
purchase invoices;
expense vouchers;
bank statements;
subscription-money records;
founder reimbursements;
payroll records;
tax deductions;
loan documentation;
vendor agreements;
customer contracts; and
asset-purchase records.

Create a clear approval process for expenditure and reimbursements. Payments made personally by founders on behalf of the company should be documented and accounted for rather than informally adjusted.

10. Review Tax and Operational Registrations

Not every company requires every registration. Applicability depends on the nature and scale of the business.

Review whether the company requires:

GST Registration

GST registration may become necessary based on turnover, the nature of supplies, interstate activity or other compulsory-registration provisions.

Registration should not be taken merely because every new company appears to be obtaining it. Equally, it should not be delayed where the law makes it compulsory.

Shops and Establishments Registration

State-specific Shops and Establishments legislation may apply to offices, commercial establishments and workplaces.

Requirements, timelines and procedures differ between states.

Professional Tax

Professional Tax registration or enrolment may apply in states where such a levy is in force.

EPFO and ESIC Compliance

Employment-related compliance should be reviewed when employees are appointed. Applicability depends on the law governing the establishment, employee strength and other prescribed conditions.

Import Export Code

A company proposing to import or export goods should assess whether it needs an Import Export Code and related customs or product-specific registrations.

Udyam Registration

Eligible micro, small and medium enterprises may consider Udyam registration for formal recognition and access to applicable benefits.

Sector-Specific Licences

Depending on the business, additional approvals may include:

FSSAI registration or licence;
trade licence;
pollution-control consent;
factory registration;
drug or cosmetic licence;
RBI or financial-sector approval;
telecom or technology permissions;
legal-metrology registration;
fire-safety approval; and
local municipal permissions.

The object clause in the Memorandum permits the company to pursue its stated business. It does not automatically replace licences required under other laws.

11. Protect the Brand and Business Relationships

The first 90 days are also the right time to establish the company’s commercial foundation.

Consider:

trademark protection for the brand name and logo;
founder or shareholder agreements;
employment and consultancy agreements;
vendor contracts;
customer terms and conditions;
privacy policy;
refund or cancellation policy;
intellectual-property assignment;
confidentiality agreements; and
website legal disclosures.

A registered company name does not automatically give complete trademark protection. Corporate registration and trademark registration serve different legal purposes.

12. Build an Annual Compliance Calendar

After the immediate post-incorporation work is completed, prepare an annual compliance calendar.

It should track:

Board meetings;
Annual General Meeting;
financial-statement preparation;
statutory audit;
income-tax return;
annual ROC filings;
GST returns, where registered;
TDS deposits and returns;
payroll compliance;
director KYC;
licence renewals; and
event-based filings.

Assign responsibility for every item. A deadline without an owner is merely a future problem.

The compliance calendar should also account for event-based changes such as:

appointment or resignation of directors;
change of registered office;
alteration of capital;
issue or transfer of shares;
creation of a charge;
borrowing;
related-party transactions; and
amendment of the Memorandum or Articles.
Common Post-Incorporation Mistakes

New companies frequently make the following mistakes:

treating the Certificate of Incorporation as completion of the entire process;
mixing personal and company funds;
delaying receipt of subscription money;
missing the first Board meeting;
failing to appoint the first auditor;
delaying INC-20A until the final days;
issuing incorrect or unstamped share certificates;
not maintaining statutory registers;
beginning operations without activity-specific licences;
ignoring accounting because the company has little or no revenue; and
using incomplete legal details on invoices and official correspondence.

Most of these problems are avoidable when the company follows a documented post-incorporation checklist.

Final Thoughts

Company registration gives an enterprise its legal birth. Compliance gives it discipline, credibility and continuity.

The first 90 days should be used to establish clean banking, governance, accounting, ownership and regulatory systems. A well-maintained company is easier to operate, finance, audit, scale and eventually transfer or invest in.

